  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "Oxidative stress response in E. coli is mediated by two major transcriptional regulators: OxyR (responds to hydrogen peroxide) and SoxRS (responds to superoxide). OxyR exists as a tetramer that senses H2O2 through oxidation of cysteine residues, forming an intramolecular disulfide bond that activates DNA binding and transcription of ~30 genes including catalase (katG), alkyl hydroperoxide reductase (ahpC), and glutathione reductase (gor). SoxRS is a two-component cascade where superoxide oxidizes the [2Fe-2S] cluster in SoxR, which then activates SoxS transcription. SoxS activates ~100 genes including superoxide dismutase (sodA), DNA repair enzymes, and efflux pumps. Both systems provide rapid, graded responses to oxidative damage with distinct but overlapping regulons. This flowchart illustrates both pathways from oxidant detection through gene activation and cellular protection.",
  "id": "ecoli_oxidative_stress_response",
